[{"sha":"e96ae7913a2534f836a92b4a1aebf403a31d6b8a","author":{"name":"Katherine Wu","email":"3597b8ab71b66d46ec439caf0c075cd0b82fcc57@google.com"},"message":"Export StructuredCoder as an internal API.

StructuredCoder is the only thing that decodes the input signatures from the SavedModel concrete functions, and Keras uses it to build the layers loaded from config. The layers must be built before loading the other functions/objects from the SavedModel in order to prevent them from creating new sublayers (which would not have the correct weights). Thus, we can't remove the use of StructuredCoder from Keras right now.

[{"sha":"b31c2073f058ee979e2085473ffff274f82eeefd","author":{"name":"Dimitris Vardoulakis","email":"532a0f5dcb324b87a62941a290161c72e1fa9537@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:HLO] Cleanly destruct fusion instructions and their computations.

If a fusion instruction dies before its computation, the computation becomes unreachable, but it may not be destructed until later. In this case, we need to clear its back-pointer to the fusion instruction, otherwise it will point to freed memory. Similarly, when a fusion computation dies, we must clear the fusion instructions's called_computations_.

We also add a boolean field in HloComputation to determine if it is a fusion computation, since with this CL we can have (unreachable) fusion computations whose fusion instruction is null.

Last, do a nullptr check during module cloning, to avoid runtime errors due to unreachable computations.

[{"sha":"0bb0d612563802e9c4c36e1c310c92ba2224154f","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Fix missing func def's when using custom kernel creators

Previously, when using custom kernel creators the function library runtime being
passed to the custom `CreateKernel` call was the wrong one (different from
other `CreateKernel` call) which led to missing func def's in following
scenario:
1) Custom kernel creator is used.
2) `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateKernel` is called directly from
   `FunctionLibraryRuntimeImpl::CreateItem`.
3) The `item` uses a function library runtime overlay which contains func def's
   that are missing from `this`.

[{"sha":"11ef8d3ba983d6fb0b1597e715bf45e3b882a507","author":{"name":"Akihiro Suda","email":"10ddef0dea2a66ab193b07198faa879adcb213d8@hco.ntt.co.jp"},"message":"overlay2: support "userxattr" option (kernel 5.11)

The "userxattr" option is needed for mounting overlayfs inside a user namespace with kernel >= 5.11.

The "userxattr" option is NOT needed for the initial user namespace (aka "the host").

Also, Ubuntu (since circa 2015) and Debian (since 10) with kernel < 5.11 can mount the overlayfs in a user namespace without the "userxattr" option.

The corresponding kernel commit: 2d2f2d7322ff43e0fe92bf8cccdc0b09449bf2e1
> **ovl: user xattr**
>
> Optionally allow using "user.overlay." namespace instead of "trusted.overlay."
> ...
> Disable redirect_dir and metacopy options, because these would allow privilege escalation through direct manipulation of the
> "user.overlay.redirect" or "user.overlay.metacopy" xattrs.

Fix issue 42055

Related to containerd/containerd PR 5076

[{"sha":"e31086320ea0305e2cc70490160ee30480471680","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove cli test for duplicate --net/--network opts

This seems to be testing a strange case, specifically that one can set
the `--net` and `--network` in the same command with the same network.

Indeed this used to work with older CLIs but newer ones error out when
validating the request before sending it to the daemon.

Opening this for discussion because:

1. This doesn't seem to be testing anything at all related to the rest
   of the test
2. Not really providing any value here.
3. Is testing that a technically invalid option is successful (whether
   the option should be valid as it relates to the CLI accepting it is
   debatable).
4. Such a case seems fringe and even a bug in whatever is calling the
   CLI with such options.

[{"sha":"4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix handling for json-file io.UnexpectedEOF

When the multireader hits EOF, we will always get EOF from it, so we
cannot store the multrireader fro later error handling, only for the
decoder.

Thanks @tobiasstadler for pointing this error out.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/moby/moby/commits/4be98a38e7810940c260d778cfe128b97d9245fb"},{"sha":"5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"jsonfile: more defensive reader implementation

Tonis mentioned that we can run into issues if there is more error
handling added here. This adds a custom reader implementation which is
like io.MultiReader except it does not cache EOF's.
What got us into trouble in the first place is `io.MultiReader` will
always return EOF once it has received an EOF, however the error
handling that we are going for is to recover from an EOF because the
underlying file is a file which can have more data added to it after
EOF.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/moby/moby/commits/5a664dc87d79ddc9f09c7a963c52f491999dc939"},{"sha":"788f2883d285fc997d25cd27235c5b17cf3c0947","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"4876a66208932b3750ccc18b302877b042a311b1@hey.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #42104 from cpuguy83/41820_fix_json_unexpected_eof","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/moby/moby/commits/788f2883d285fc997d25cd27235c5b17cf3c0947"}]

[{"sha":"e79f204cc6c9762a2a6bec0cea549dd613ffc811","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Remove guards around b/143684500.

Several kernels have previously been disabled for std::complex due
to lack of operator support on device.  This is no longer the case,
and these kernels can now be enabled.

NOTE: we also needed to replace `a+=b` and `a-=b` with `a=a+b` and
`a=a-b` for use with `std::complex<T>` on device.  Unfortunately MSVC
does not stricly follow the c++ standard, and unnecessarily specializes
these operators. This prevents us from using Eigen's device-compatible
overrides.  Without these overrides, the original compound assignments
`+=` and `-=` silently fail on GPU.
